<header class="header">
      <h1>Seed Starting Schedule for Short Growing Seasons</h1>
      <p class="tagline">
        A clear method for planning indoor starts and transplant timing.
      </p>
      <p class="lede">
        In short growing seasons, timing is constrained by frost at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong>.
        A schedule works best when it’s built around your typical last frost timing (spring) and the limited season length that follows.
        That approach keeps planning deterministic and reduces maturity risk in a typical year.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Start With One Anchor Date</h2>

      <p>
        Every spring plan begins with your <strong>average last frost date</strong> at <strong>32°F</strong>.
        On GrowByDate, this is framed using 1991–2020 climate normals at the <strong>50% probability</strong> level
        (historically, a 50% chance of frost on or after that date).
      </p>

      <p>
        That anchor date becomes the reference point for:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>Indoor seed starting windows</li>
        <li>Hardening off periods</li>
        <li>Outdoor transplant timing</li>
        <li>Direct sow windows</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        To find your typical last frost date for your location, start with the
        <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Instead of guessing when to plant, count backward (or forward) from that climate boundary.
        If you prefer to generate these windows automatically, use the
        <a href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">Seed Starting Planner</a>.
      </p>

      <p class="fine">
        Short-season planning works best when you treat frost timing as the boundary and your season length as the available window.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>The 3 Planning Windows That Matter</h2>

      <h3>1. Indoor Start Window</h3>
      <p>
        Most warm-season crops need a 6–10 week head start indoors in shorter climates.
        Count backward from your typical last frost date to determine when to sow so seedlings are ready when outdoor risk drops.
      </p>

      <p>
        Starting too early can create plants that outgrow their containers while waiting for outdoor conditions.
        Starting too late reduces the effective season available for heat accumulation and maturity.
      </p>

      <h3>2. Hardening Off Period</h3>
      <p>
        Plan 7–10 days before transplanting to gradually expose seedlings to wind, sun, and temperature swings.
        In a typical short season, skipping this step can cause a stall after transplant that costs valuable growing time.
      </p>

      <p>
        If you need a structured hardening plan, see
        <a href="/guides/how-to-harden-off-seedlings/">How to Harden Off Seedlings</a>.
      </p>

      <h3>3. Transplant or Direct Sow Window</h3>
      <p>
        Warm-season crops are usually transplanted after the last frost boundary.
        Cool-season crops may be planted slightly before it, depending on cold tolerance.
      </p>

      <p>
        The goal is to align outdoor planting with declining frost risk while maximizing the remaining season length for development.
        For crops that are maturity-limited, that development window is best understood as a heat budget (Growing Degree Days).
      </p>

      <p>
        To estimate how much heat typically accumulates after your frost boundary, use the
        <a href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Growing Degree Day Planner</a>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Which Crops Should You Start Indoors?</h2>

      <p><strong>Usually started indoors (short-season advantage):</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/crops/tomatoes/">Tomatoes</a></li>
        <li><a href="/crops/peppers/">Peppers</a></li>
        <li>Broccoli</li>
        <li>Cabbage</li>
        <li>Kale</li>
      </ul>

      <p><strong>Usually direct sown:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Spinach</li>
        <li>Beans</li>
        <li>Carrots</li>
        <li>Radishes</li>
      </ul>

      <p>
        In shorter seasons, giving warm crops a controlled indoor start increases the odds that they reach maturity
        before first frost returns in fall.
      </p>

      <p>
        If you want the underlying planning logic explained step-by-step, see
        <a href="/guides/counting-backward-from-frost-how-seed-timing-works/">Counting Backward From Frost: How Seed Timing Works</a>.
      </p>
    </section>